where you got the yellow one?

22:30.023 --> 22:31.631
Rosalee gave it to me.

22:32.716 --> 22:35.367
After the scary man got my momma.

22:38.180 --> 22:39.720
What scary man?

22:40.663 --> 22:42.797
Massa made him chase us.

22:45.028 --> 22:46.511
What was your master's name?

22:47.159 --> 22:48.557
Massa Tom.

22:54.321 --> 22:55.365
Macon?

22:56.645 --> 22:58.852
Is your master's name Tom Macon?

23:01.912 --> 23:04.373
More scary men got my papa, too.

23:04.508 --> 23:05.956
His name's Moses,

23:06.212 --> 23:08.796
but God didn't part the sea like he did

23:08.919 --> 23:10.174
for the one in the Bible.

23:12.139 --> 23:14.521
Why didn't he help my momma and papa?

23:17.159 --> 23:19.193
(banging on door)

23:23.319 --> 23:24.937
You have to hide now.

23:25.435 --> 23:27.902
♪ ♪

23:42.752 --> 23:45.870
KYLE:
I heard you ran
into a cherry-picker

23:45.922 --> 23:47.755
down at the river. Are you okay?

23:47.791 --> 23:51.709
I'm fine. They were asking
if I saw a little girl.

23:51.761 --> 23:53.205
- I haven't.
- You shouldn't be down

23:53.230 --> 23:55.070
at the river right now by yourself.

23:55.098 --> 23:56.798
- Where's John?
- He's traveling.

23:56.800 --> 23:59.050
- So you're alone?
- I'm a big girl.

23:59.102 --> 24:02.136
- I can handle myself.
- I've known you longer than most people,

24:02.189 --> 24:04.305
- I imagine. Would you say that?
- I would.

24:04.307 --> 24:06.808
KYLE: There's no question you
can take care of yourself.

24:06.860 --> 24:09.444
Never has been. Only
question I really have

24:09.479 --> 24:12.480
is, if you're alone, Bitsy,
why are there two cups of tea

24:12.532 --> 24:14.473
out here on the table?

24:15.202 --> 24:19.487
Sometimes, when I'm lonely, um...

24:19.489 --> 24:21.706
Do you think I'm a fool?

24:21.741 --> 24:24.959
(footsteps approaching)

24:24.995 --> 24:27.245
Kyle, wait.

24:27.297 --> 24:28.002
(screams)

24:28.054 --> 24:29.696
Don't hurt her. She's
just a little girl.

24:29.721 --> 24:31.395
She is a runaway, and you lied to me.

24:31.448 --> 24:32.652
He was hunting her.

24:32.654 --> 24:33.888
I won't just turn her over.

24:33.890 --> 24:35.315
I defended you.

24:35.367 --> 24:37.639
They told me they saw you with
her, and I said I knew you

24:37.674 --> 24:38.996
and that you would never. And then

24:39.021 --> 24:40.925
you lie to my face.

24:40.977 --> 24:41.946
Do you really think that little of me?

24:41.971 --> 24:43.595
I'm scared.

24:44.264 --> 24:45.570
That's why I lied.

24:46.539 --> 24:49.983
I know what you do to slave stealers.

24:50.020 --> 24:51.736
The branding...

24:52.415 --> 24:55.022
Bitsy, I would never hurt you.

24:55.909 --> 24:58.086
But it's your job.

24:59.327 --> 25:01.775
What has John gotten you mixed up in?

25:04.000 --> 25:05.867
If you were mine,

25:05.902 --> 25:09.370
I swear, I would protect
you no matter what.

25:12.000 --> 25:13.790
I'd protect your secrets, too.

25:14.942 --> 25:16.111
You know that, don't you?

25:48.378 --> 25:50.086
I want you to stay here.

25:50.839 --> 25:52.152
I will be right back.

25:52.465 --> 25:53.665
Okay? (grunts)

25:53.717 --> 25:56.718
Sweetie, I will be right back.

25:57.369 --> 25:58.722
You're safe.

25:59.656 --> 26:02.340
♪ Hush ♪

26:02.392 --> 26:05.927
♪ Hush ♪

26:05.929 --> 26:08.930
♪ Hush-a-bye ♪

26:08.982 --> 26:12.567
♪ Don't you cry ♪

26:12.602 --> 26:18.156
♪ Go to sleep-y, little baby ♪

26:18.191 --> 26:21.859
♪ When you wake ♪

26:21.911 --> 26:24.829
♪ You shall have ♪

26:24.864 --> 26:30.785
♪ All the pretty little horses ♪

26:30.787 --> 26:33.705
♪ Black and bay ♪

26:33.757 --> 26:37.375
- ♪ Dapple and gray ♪
- (door opens)

26:37.427 --> 26:43.464
♪ Coach and six white little horses ♪

26:43.466 --> 26:46.050
♪ Hush-a-bye ♪

26:46.102 --> 26:49.437
♪ Don't you cry ♪

26:49.472 --> 26:55.494
♪ Go to sleep-y, little baby. ♪

27:28.493 --> 27:30.660
- (howling in distance)
- (insects trilling)

27:34.644 --> 27:38.012
LEDGER: The crosses signal how much
cargo needs to be transported

27:38.064 --> 27:39.159
to the next station.

27:39.683 --> 27:41.395
Lets the undertaker know to build

27:41.420 --> 27:42.377
four caskets.

27:42.580 --> 27:44.166
That's the grave in the song?

27:44.320 --> 27:47.522
That's right. We'll come
back in a day or two.

27:47.574 --> 27:50.089
He'll have moved these to
angle like the hands on a clock

27:50.125 --> 27:51.071
with the sun.

27:52.585 --> 27:55.486
Tells us the days till
he's prepared to move cargo

27:55.538 --> 27:56.633
to the next station.

27:57.083 --> 27:58.166
How long you think that'll be?

27:58.201 --> 28:00.865
A week, at most. But don't worry,

28:00.900 --> 28:03.838
you'll be safe in the brush huts
hidden deep in Indian territory.

28:09.479 --> 28:11.392
Feel the ground secure beneath you

28:11.394 --> 28:13.132
before you take your next step.

28:13.466 --> 28:15.229
Then stay on that straight line.

28:16.039 --> 28:17.524
That's how your footprints stay hidden.

28:18.104 --> 28:19.303
Who taught you all this?

28:19.339 --> 28:22.319
My father and his father before him.

28:22.976 --> 28:24.976
The tribe has needed
to conceal their movements

28:25.028 --> 28:26.596
from the white man long before
I walked these lands.

28:27.476 --> 28:28.863
They part of the Underground, too?

28:29.162 --> 28:32.731
No. But they've given safe haven
to runaways for generations.

28:33.332 --> 28:34.326
My mother was one of 'em.

28:36.239 --> 28:37.538
What about your parents?

28:38.041 --> 28:39.337
What path did they walk?

28:39.993 --> 28:42.634
I never knew 'em.
I was born on a breedin' farm.

28:43.473 --> 28:45.222
<i>Means I got a lot of brothers
and sisters out there,</i>

28:45.247 --> 28:46.413
<i>I suppose.</i>

28:48.718 --> 28:50.276
<i>I ain't never had no kin.</i>

28:51.388 --> 28:53.971
(laughs)

28:56.742 --> 28:58.976
<i>Y'all run into a lot of slave catchers?</i>

28:59.012 --> 29:00.559
<i>That's why you need all this gunpowder?</i>

29:00.595 --> 29:03.107
The Underground's
best weapon is secrecy.

29:03.159 --> 29:04.673
We're building a tunnel.

29:05.185 --> 29:08.436
Aren't many homes to serve
as stations along this stretch,

29:08.488 --> 29:10.568
so we're looking for both
shelter and safe transit.

29:10.603 --> 29:12.118
How big it gonna be?

29:12.143 --> 29:15.098
- The tunnel.
- As long as we can make it.

29:17.187 --> 29:19.106
<i>Thank you for your help, Henry.</i>

29:19.255 --> 29:19.886
HENRY: You leavin'?

29:19.911 --> 29:22.025
<i>I need to see a man about the other
side of the tunnel.</i>

29:22.208 --> 29:23.558
Okay. Where we headed?

29:23.920 --> 29:26.417
LEDGER:
<i>I need to keep a light track</i>
<i>on this one.</i>

29:27.003 --> 29:28.415
The Patty Cannon gang
is still on the hunt

29:28.440 --> 29:29.752
for your group.

29:30.580 --> 29:31.913
<i>Besides, I'm sure</i>

29:31.938 --> 29:34.131
<i>your people are concerned
with where you been.</i>

29:39.392 --> 29:40.384
Where'd you get that from?

29:40.437 --> 29:41.543
What you want, boy?

29:42.806 --> 29:44.939
I thought maybe you could teach
me some more fight,

29:44.974 --> 29:46.893
- like you did on the boa...
- So, Noah dropped you for that girl,

29:46.918 --> 29:48.595
now you want to saddle up next to me?

29:49.407 --> 29:50.471
<i>You can't blame him.</i>

29:51.228 --> 29:53.228
She well made, ain't she?

29:53.700 --> 29:56.027
But you wouldn't know nothin'
about that, do you?

29:57.153 --> 29:59.287
Gettin' between a woman's legs.

29:59.812 --> 30:02.361
Nah. That's a man's business.

30:02.386 --> 30:03.961
And you just a boy.

30:03.986 --> 30:05.626
Runnin' around here lookin' all pitiful

30:05.662 --> 30:07.994
'cause you ain't
Noah's favorite no more.

30:19.843 --> 30:21.559
(birds chirping)

30:25.982 --> 30:28.149
- (hoofbeats in distance)
- (men speaking indistinctly)

30:34.190 --> 30:36.324
(frogs croaking)

30:51.708 --> 30:53.808
(howling in distance)

30:59.582 --> 31:01.716
(insects trilling)

31:06.689 --> 31:09.223
Been waitin' a while
for you to get back.

31:09.275 --> 31:12.014
I checked the crosses. They
gonna be ready for us tomorrow.

31:12.039 --> 31:13.861
I would've gone with you.

31:13.897 --> 31:15.787
Thought you were with Rosalee.

31:17.291 --> 31:18.646
What's all this for?

31:20.203 --> 31:23.204
You always talkin' about how
you want a tattoo like mine.

31:23.675 --> 31:25.707
So I had Ledger
help me make up some ink.

31:27.528 --> 31:29.660
Yeah. Okay.

31:41.594 --> 31:43.793
I've been thinkin' a lot
about last names lately.

31:43.999 --> 31:44.823
Why?

31:46.099 --> 31:48.142
You know, on the plantation,
I feel like I saw

31:48.167 --> 31:49.878
that Macon name everywhere.

31:50.233 --> 31:53.068
On work orders.
That iron gate at the bridge.

31:53.120 --> 31:54.527
Heard it everywhere, too.

31:55.274 --> 31:56.857
There's a lot of power in a name.

31:57.223 --> 31:58.735
There's history, kinship.

31:58.944 --> 32:00.479
It ties you to family.

32:01.664 --> 32:03.280
Now we gettin' closer to freedom,

32:03.996 --> 32:05.703
we gonna have a lot of choices to make.

32:06.392 --> 32:07.802
Where we gonna live.

32:08.535 --> 32:09.839
What we gonna do.

32:10.956 --> 32:13.274
Figure we ought to start with a name.

32:15.127 --> 32:16.495
Henry Hampton.

32:19.303 --> 32:21.183
Noah and Henry Hampton.

32:40.596 --> 32:42.395
You ain't got to cook for us.

32:42.988 --> 32:45.289
I mean, it ain't on you

32:45.324 --> 32:46.315
if you don't want to.

32:47.886 --> 32:48.948
I don't mind.

32:49.545 --> 32:50.827
It remind me of home.

32:51.628 --> 32:52.671
The big house?

32:53.500 --> 32:55.082
My momma.

32:57.357 --> 32:59.305
Yeah, forgot you left family behind.

33:03.409 --> 33:05.468
She could make a meal out of anything.

33:06.213 --> 33:08.060
They gives us scraps.

33:08.314 --> 33:10.188
We make a feast, she say.

33:12.398 --> 33:13.934
Maybe you teach me.

33:18.762 --> 33:20.195
I'd like that.

33:24.697 --> 33:26.161
- What you think about the name...?
- (gunshot)

33:26.163 --> 33:27.123
(screams)

33:27.616 --> 33:29.082
MAN: That was a warning shot!

33:29.118 --> 33:31.158
Move! Get inside, come on!

33:32.204 --> 33:33.670
MAN 2: We got you surrounded!
Come on out!

33:33.706 --> 33:35.038
They behind us, too.

33:35.040 --> 33:36.340
MAN 3: I'll give you
to the count of ten!

33:36.375 --> 33:38.125
- How we gonna get through 'em?
- Nine...

33:38.177 --> 33:39.760
- eight...
- Noah!

33:39.795 --> 33:40.596
seven,

33:40.621 --> 33:41.712
The gunpowder in the hut across the way.

33:41.714 --> 33:42.970
- six...
- We blow our way out.

33:42.995 --> 33:45.265
- five... four...
- We need fire.

33:45.300 --> 33:46.653
- three...
- The hut's too far.

33:46.655 --> 33:48.969
- two...
- You'll never make it.

33:49.004 --> 33:51.555
- (gunshots)
- (grunting)

33:58.079 --> 33:59.128
(grunting) No! No!

33:59.357 --> 34:00.562
Henry!

34:04.990 --> 34:06.517
Henry!

34:21.225 --> 34:23.175
♪ Summertime ♪

34:23.226 --> 34:27.563
♪ And the livin' is easy ♪

34:27.598 --> 34:30.149
♪ Fish are jumpin' ♪

34:30.184 --> 34:34.853
♪ And the cotton is high ♪

34:34.906 --> 34:38.491
♪ Oh, your daddy's rich ♪

34:38.525 --> 34:42.610
♪ And your mommy's good lookin' ♪

34:42.612 --> 34:44.112
When's lunch ready?

34:44.114 --> 34:45.915
- Soon.
- When's James coming back?

34:45.949 --> 34:47.416
It's hard to tell.

34:47.452 --> 34:48.614
Is he coming back?

34:51.039 --> 34:52.338
Go on now.

34:52.373 --> 34:54.623
These'll hold you over till lunch ready.

34:54.625 --> 34:56.676
(indistinct chatter)

34:56.710 --> 34:59.084
CARVER: It's not about holding the line.

34:59.109 --> 35:00.541
It's about pushing in...

35:01.762 --> 35:03.595
T.R., where's your head at?

35:04.375 --> 35:05.317
What do you say?

35:05.553 --> 35:06.686
Sorry.

35:09.724 --> 35:11.390
Getting too old to play with toys,

35:11.442 --> 35:12.525
young man.

35:12.560 --> 35:13.940
Yes, sir.

35:15.868 --> 35:17.780
How about you and I

35:17.815 --> 35:19.532
head over to the stables,

35:20.021 --> 35:21.651
get you up on a real horse, huh?

35:21.652 --> 35:22.985
What do you say?

35:23.037 --> 35:23.986
(horse snorts)

35:23.988 --> 35:26.122
There you go. (chuckles)

35:26.157 --> 35:27.725
How's that feel?

35:28.159 --> 35:29.375
Wobbly.

35:29.750 --> 35:32.128
Well, you just hold those reins tight.

35:32.163 --> 35:33.496
Let the horse know who's in control.

35:33.498 --> 35:35.111
Daddy, look.

35:36.056 --> 35:37.504
I see you, son.

35:38.336 --> 35:39.969
(whip cracks)

35:40.004 --> 35:42.728
Ha! Ha! Easy now!

35:42.780 --> 35:43.973
Why is he hitting him?

35:44.008 --> 35:45.007
TOM: They're training the horse.

35:45.059 --> 35:46.308
So it'll be able to be ridden.

35:46.344 --> 35:47.341
Just like the one you're on.

35:47.393 --> 35:48.388
But they're hurting him.

35:48.413 --> 35:49.713
It's a necessary measure.

35:50.133 --> 35:52.014
The horses are useless
to us in their wild state.

35:52.016 --> 35:53.349
They will break free

35:53.401 --> 35:55.518
unless you snap out
their will to resist.

35:55.570 --> 35:57.069
A good trainer knows that

35:57.105 --> 35:59.822
you have to take a horse from
its independent state of nature

35:59.857 --> 36:01.724
and create a dependent state,

36:01.759 --> 36:03.526
so they will become
more productive to our needs.

36:03.578 --> 36:04.744
(trainer shouting)

36:04.779 --> 36:06.829
- (horse snorting)
- Whoa!

36:08.948 --> 36:10.301
He doesn't seem to like it.

36:10.421 --> 36:11.200
<i>She.</i>

36:12.931 --> 36:14.203
You see, efforts are best spent

36:14.255 --> 36:15.217
breaking the females.

36:15.923 --> 36:17.206
Then she will pass along

36:17.208 --> 36:19.125
those learned traits to her foal.

36:20.151 --> 36:21.472
When you get 'em young enough,

36:22.281 --> 36:24.552
you can get them to do almost anything.

36:31.835 --> 36:33.472
Hey, James!

36:37.077 --> 36:37.973
Son.

36:39.805 --> 36:41.614
Look to the right, okay?

36:43.284 --> 36:45.651
Look as far as you can. Then left.

36:46.164 --> 36:47.372
As far as you can.

36:48.796 --> 36:51.068
Look at everything else in-between.

36:52.543 --> 36:53.626
I don't see anything.

36:53.661 --> 36:55.779
What you see is Macon land.

36:56.414 --> 36:58.080
All this is gonna be yours someday.

36:58.565 --> 36:59.800
Every acre.

37:00.291 --> 37:01.050
Hey, why don't you start

37:01.085 --> 37:02.384
learning what it is I do,

37:02.420 --> 37:03.913
'cause you gonna be me one day.

37:04.986 --> 37:06.590
And I'll own everything?

37:06.591 --> 37:07.817
Yes, sir.

37:09.927 --> 37:10.976
Even James?

37:11.012 --> 37:12.761
James, Stine...

37:12.814 --> 37:13.896
all the slaves.

37:13.931 --> 37:15.097
They're gonna be your property

37:15.149 --> 37:16.305
just like this horse.

37:20.271 --> 37:21.889
Your Grandpa Earl...

37:22.981 --> 37:25.216
he didn't think that this
whole plot was arable.

37:25.883 --> 37:26.813
You know what "arable" means?

37:27.945 --> 37:29.069
Good for growing crops.

37:29.530 --> 37:31.780
But I knew a man from up
north... a quarry master.

37:31.782 --> 37:33.666
He pulled out all the shale.

37:33.701 --> 37:35.997
All we had to do was plant more cotton.

37:37.309 --> 37:39.622
Now, I've improved upon this plantation

37:39.941 --> 37:41.625
out of love for this land,

37:42.093 --> 37:44.426
which is what I hope
you'll do when I'm gone.

37:45.465 --> 37:46.762
I can do that.

37:47.257 --> 37:48.631
You can, can you?

37:49.728 --> 37:51.067
(knocking)

37:52.822 --> 37:54.103
Pardon, massa, uh...

37:55.128 --> 37:56.188
can I have a word?

37:56.224 --> 37:57.640
Absolutely, Sam. Come on in.

37:59.848 --> 38:00.609
My son

38:00.645 --> 38:02.811
is becoming familiar
with the day-to-day operations

38:02.813 --> 38:04.613
of the plantation, so

38:04.649 --> 38:06.532
anything that you have to say,
you can say

38:06.567 --> 38:07.496
right in front of him.

38:10.625 --> 38:12.071
That desk is...

38:12.409 --> 38:15.117
that desk looking mighty fine in here.

38:15.168 --> 38:16.126
It sure does.

38:16.544 --> 38:17.369
It's a beauty.

38:17.662 --> 38:19.328
I remember when you made it, Sam.

38:19.380 --> 38:21.463
That's when I realized
that you had a gift.

38:21.769 --> 38:23.299
That's the first time you paid me.

38:24.074 --> 38:25.167
That's right, I did.

38:25.440 --> 38:26.602
You have a very good memory.

38:26.637 --> 38:28.053
I told you to save your money, right?

38:28.633 --> 38:30.005
Now that's very important, son.

38:30.007 --> 38:32.305
'Cause a man's only
as good as his savings.

38:36.398 --> 38:37.680
And I never spent the one!

38:38.451 --> 38:39.451
Good man.

38:40.197 --> 38:41.684
Now I want to spend them all.

38:43.053 --> 38:44.354
On what?

38:47.925 --> 38:49.525
You also said that, uh,

38:50.069 --> 38:52.277
I work hard enough one day,
I might be able to...

38:52.613 --> 38:54.236
I could buy my freedom.

38:58.044 --> 38:58.751
Sam...

38:58.786 --> 39:00.869
Now, massa, this, uh...

39:04.842 --> 39:06.844
There's near $100 in that jar.

39:07.701 --> 39:08.807
That's impressive.

39:09.096 --> 39:10.546
That's very impressive.

39:13.089 --> 39:14.134
But, Sam, truth be told,

39:14.185 --> 39:15.428
you're worth five of those jars.

39:16.803 --> 39:19.723
And I would be a very
bad businessman if I let

39:19.724 --> 39:20.923
my most prized nigger go.

39:22.669 --> 39:24.025
I ain't being clear.

39:24.892 --> 39:26.228
That ain't for my freedom.

39:26.280 --> 39:27.896
(clears throat)

39:28.732 --> 39:30.149
It's for James.

39:36.508 --> 39:38.073
James is just a boy.

39:38.791 --> 39:40.209
Where would he go without his family?

39:41.092 --> 39:42.127
He could stay with me.

39:42.605 --> 39:43.659
You could hire me out

39:43.711 --> 39:45.571
in the city, and you know
how hard I work.

39:45.624 --> 39:48.217
Just the other day, Mr. Calloway
he paid me ten dollars.

39:48.252 --> 39:49.918
Ten dollars for a chair I made for him.

39:49.920 --> 39:51.460
You know they'd pay more

39:51.472 --> 39:52.645
if they knew that money going to you.

39:52.670 --> 39:54.256
Now's not really the right time.

39:54.258 --> 39:55.724
But I'll consider your proposal.

39:55.760 --> 39:57.242
Massa, please.

39:57.928 --> 39:59.028
Mr. Bill, he,

39:59.397 --> 40:01.146
his eyes is stuck on James.

40:01.182 --> 40:02.431
He mad as a rattlesnake

40:02.433 --> 40:03.932
after what Rosalee done done.

40:04.325 --> 40:05.684
All right, I'll talk to Bill.

40:06.013 --> 40:06.902
Now I promised

40:06.937 --> 40:08.187
